<div class="section-title">
  <h2><span>Scope of the Study</span></h2>
</div>

<div class="centered-column">
  <h3 class="no-margin-top">Goals</h3>
  <p>Our client wanted to understand whether and to what extent the current incarnation of the web app adheres to the <a href="http://www.wqusability.com/articles/getting-started.html" target="_blank">"Five E’s" of usability</a>&mdash;in particular, "easy to use" and "efficient". From there, we came up with five research questions to answer:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Are new users able to find and use the main functionalities when creating a presentation?</li>
    <li>Is the slideshow creation web app efficient for creating presentations?</li>
    <li>What obstacles do users encounter in the process of creating a deck?</li>
    <li>Are users satisfied by the appearance of the final output?</li>
    <li>Are features easy to learn and re-use?</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Target User Group</h3>
  <p>According to the company’s market research, the current major user groups of Haiku Deck are students, teachers, real estate agents, bloggers, and business people. Since Haiku Deck’s target user population is so vast, we decided to focus on a subset of their current users: students.</p>
  <p>As students, we were in a better position to quickly and easily recruit student participants, and we also believed they were more likely than professionals to be available to participate in our research given our limited budget.</p>

  <h3>Interaction Map</h3>
  <p>To fully understand the product, we tried it ourselves and as a result created an interaction map. The interaction map represents all actions a user can perform using the software. Creating the map forced us to explore every aspect of the product, and we even ran into hidden features.</p>
</div>

