<div class="section-title">
  <h2><span>Usability Plan</span></h2>
</div>

<div class="columns">
  <h3 class="no-margin-top">Participants</h3>
  <p>Because learnability is an important aspect of using such a software, we created two distinct participant groups: new users and existing users.</p>
  <p>Because Haiku Deck was a new product, we couldn't easily find existing users. Instead, we asked to half of the participants to use Haiku Deck for one of their class presentations before the study.<p>
  </p>We also made sure to recruit participants from different backgrounds (business, engineering, and communication) as it also could impact results. We designed a screening questionnaire to select only qualified participants in the right proportions.</p>

  <h3>Tasks</h3>
  <p>From the research questions and the initial review of the software, we listed specific questions that we wanted to answer, how to collect the data, and evaluate findings.</p>
  <p>Then, we created a list of ten tasks for users to complete. Tasks were part of a larger scenario&mdash;creating a presentation about Seattle for your uncle living in another state. For each task, task completion, and time on task was measured.</p>
  <p>Finally, pre and post study questionnaires, as well as post task questionnaires allowed us to gather more qualitative information about the participant's experience.</p>

  <h3>Test Environment</h3>
  <p>The lab usability sessions took place at the University of Washington using the software Morae to record and monitor each individual one hour session. A member of the team stayed in the room with the participant to moderate the session, and the other team members observed and took time-stamped notes remotely.</p>
</div>

